        <td bgcolor="black" colspan="2"  valign="top">
		<a name="62797"></a>
		<img src="icon_posticon.gif" border="0" hspace="3"><font color="white" face="Verdana" size="2">Posted&nbsp;-&nbsp;08/25/2002&nbsp;:&nbsp; 00:32:57</font>

		&nbsp;<a href="pop_profile.asp?mode=display&amp;id=782"><img src="icon_profile.gif" height="15" width="15" alt="Show Profile" border="0" align="absmiddle" hspace="6"></a>
        
			&nbsp;<a href="JavaScript:openWindow('pop_mail.asp?id=782')"><img src="icon_email.gif" height="15" width="15" alt="Email Poster" border="0" align="absmiddle" hspace="6"></a>

        &nbsp;<a href="post.asp?method=ReplyQuote&amp;REPLY_ID=62797&amp;TOPIC_ID=7515&amp;FORUM_ID=2&amp;CAT_ID=1&amp;Forum_Title=General+Discussions&amp;Topic_Title=Cleric+pet+%2D+now+VI+went+overboard&amp;M="><img src="icon_reply_topic.gif" height="15" width="15" alt="Reply with Quote" border="0" align="absmiddle" hspace="6"></a>

        <hr noshade size="2" color="#545A7D">
        
         You made a cleric to heal.  I made a necro to be the master of the dead and to deal damage.  Yet what I can do to undead, enchanters can do to anything and better.  Though I can do damage, I am not the best at dealing it.</P><P>While it is unfortunate that clerics, who have long been the dominant healing class, must now compete directly with druids and shamans for grouping spots and raiding spots, it is something that, IMO, must be done.  Tnere has long existed a great imbalance between the priest classes due primarily to the huge gap in healing prowess, which led, in part, to the "casterization" of the priest classes, by which I mean the comparison that is often drawn between casters and druids/shamans because of the latter's similarity to us - not as healers, but as offensive casters.  The root of all of this, of course, is one of the worst mistakes VI has ever made in designing the game: Complete Heal.</P><P>Clerics have depended on this spell and this spell alone for their healing superiority.  Without CH, the cleric class is broken.  Yet all the same, it is CH that has caused some of the most terrible design decisions in the history of EQ, for example: monsters that hit for absurd amounts of damage.  Without CH, EQ would be a very different game.  The AoW would not be quadding for 1000+ points of damage and flurrying.  No, he would be more likely hitting around the 500's, and the heals of other classes (shamans, druids, paladins, and to a degree necros) would not be so insignificant as to be pointless.  </P><P>Yet to get rid of CH now is foolishness - it would mean redesigning ALL of EQ's high-end encounters and that is not very smart.  The only fair thing to do is to give CH to other priest classes, and make no mistake, I completely agree with Rich: healing is too important a role for one class to dominate so completely.  You cannot do high-end raids without a LARGE number of clerics, period - no matter how many druids/shamans you have.  This holds true for only two other classes: warriors and (in Luclin) mages.  All other classes could be pretty much replaced or be present in very minimal numbers. </P><P>Yet having given such a vital, pivotal ability of the cleric class to other classes, VI must now face the challenge of redesigning this class that is broken had CH been taken away.  In many ways, the loosening of the cleric noose on healing is a GOOD thing for clerics, because now all the other clerical issues can be brought to the surface and dealt with.  No longer must clerics hide behind the overpowering Complete Heal which, in given clerics dominance over all healers, so too blocks other facets of the class from developing (and thus making clerics "very boring and repetitive" in addition to being overpowered for raids).  It might almost be fitting to say that we have taken off the cleric's golden mask, and in doing so come to witness the pale and shriveled man beneath - a man who has hidden too long behind one thing, that the rest of him have degenerated.</P><P>Perhaps I, not being a cleric, does not understand.  But perhaps it is *because* I am not a cleric that I am able to remain objective and unbiased about this.  There will ALWAYS be cynics within any community who will fight change even if the end result was much better.  The clerics WILL whine about this and I fully expect them to for a long time after the changes are made.  I'd even say that clerics have a right to complain about this change.  I have no doubt that there will be a small group who will ALWAYS be whining even if clerics become better than they are now after the changes.  That is human nature. </P><P>But the TRUE test of this change will come after it is made.  The true test will be how clerics are improved - how that weak little class below the visage of CH will be helped to stand shoulder-to-shoulder with druids and shamans in the greater scheme of things.  It is the success or failure of this that will determine the future of clerics, and it is this that the cleric community should pay the most attention to now.  </P><P>It is true that clerics might indeed be "nerfed" by this change, and <BR>that they may never regain their former power and influence, and this is something that clerics everywhere will just have to accept.  But I ask the cleric community to consider this: is casting CHs really all you want out of the cleric class? Is it better to be uber, but in being so, become nothing more than a one-button wonder? </P><P></P><P><BR>Etadanik the Redeemed<a href="#top"><img src="icon_go_up.gif" height="15" width="15" border="0" align="right" alt="Go to Top of Page"></a></font></td>
      </tr>

